title: Mental health in workplace campaign kicks off
content_text: Employers and managers need to build a work environment which is conducive to promoting the mental health of their employees, Chairman of the Rehabilitation Advisory Committee, Dr Raymond Wu, said today (October 10). Officiating at the opening ceremony of the 2001 Mental Health Month, Dr Wu said that living in a place renowned for its high work efficiency and fast pace of life such as Hong Kong, one had to be doubly careful about his mental health. "Through this year's activities, we hope to be able to draw the attention of

this year's activities, we hope to be able to draw the attention of
employers and managers to the importance of their employees' mental health
and the need to build a harmonious and happy workplace." Also
officiating at today's ceremony were Mental Health Ambassador, Mr Allen
Lee; Director of Home Affairs, Ms Shelley Lee; Director of Health, Dr
Margaret Chan; Chief Executive of the Hospital Authority, Dr William Ho;
Director of Social Welfare, Mrs Carrie Lam; Commissioner for Labour, Mrs
Pamela Tan; and Deputy Secretary for the Civil Service, Miss Jennifer Mak. The

Pamela Tan; and Deputy Secretary for the Civil Service, Miss Jennifer Mak. The
Mental Health Month is an annual publicity campaign organized by the
Health and Welfare Bureau with the support of the Hospital Authority,
various government departments and NGOs to promote public awareness on the
importance of mental health. Entitled
"Mental Health in the Workplace", this year's campaign is aimed
at enhancing the awareness of employers and employees on mental health and
ways to deal with stress. The theme, extending over two years from 2000 to

ways to deal with stress. The theme, extending over two years from 2000 to
2001, is to tie in with the World Mental Health Day which allows a broader
examination of matters affecting employees at every level. Today's
opening ceremony was followed by a one-day symposium which was attended by
about 600 employers and mangers. Guest speakers included managers from
private and public enterprises, a clinical psychologist, and experts on
mental health issues in the workplace. In the
ensuing three months, more than 70 activities - talks, workshops,

ensuing three months, more than 70 activities - talks, workshops,
exhibitions, recreational activities and visits - will be held across the
territory.  Among them are five regional symposia to promote a
healthy workplace for employers and employees. Details are as follows: Date:
